BLASTOMYCOSIS - USA: (WISCONSIN), TUBING, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 31 Jul 2015
Source: Greenbay.com [edited]
http://www.wearegreenbay.com/story/d/story/woman-claims-tubing-trip-lead-to-fungal-infection/36837/tr0ouLg_PkOK41xCXdfErA


A posting has gone viral on Facebook. In it, a local woman claims several of her friends contracted a dangerous fungus while tubing down the Little Wolf River. Blastomycosis is a fungal infection [that] causes flu-like symptoms and respiratory issues.

[The patient] says a month ago she and a group of friends came to the Wolf River Campground in New London [Wisconsin] to go tubing. Afterwards she and 3 friends became ill, all diagnosed with the same fungal infection, blastomycosis, eventually landing her and another friend in the hospital. "It makes sense that all the people who got sick were with me at the time," said [the patient].

According to the CDC, blastomycosis [disease-causing spores] live in soil in decaying organic matter. Fungal spores become airborne when soil is disturbed, and a person becomes ill after breathing in those spores.

[The patient] recalled when she believes she was exposed: "Usually, you float down, and there is a little island you stop at; so we were climbing up, and on top, there is a bunch of wood, and it's really muddy," [the patient] said.

But at the Wolf River Campground, managers question [the patient]'s claim since no one who became ill ever contacted them. "I don't feel there is anything wrong out on the water," said Richard Flease, a campground manager. "If any health officials have anything to say about it, we'll definitely look into it. But as of now, we have not heard from anybody except from this group of 4 people."

Outagamie County's Health Department says they have one confirmed case, know of one in another county, and have alerted the state. The Waupaca County Health Department says they have no complaints.

"It really is scary; that is why I'm trying to get the word out," [the patient] explained. But at the Wolf River Campground, for now, it's business as usual. "We have lots of people out here each weekend, and I would have thought we'd have a few more reports on it," Flease said.

An infectious disease expert told Local 5 that all who became ill also work at the same business and that it's too early to say with any certainty how they contracted the illness.

[Byline: Kris Schuller]

